FROM: E:src/pd

arexxport:      Leon Woestenberg
                    (leon@stack.urc.tue.nl, done)
                "Examples are good, but it's not my idea to re-write the
                 C= Autodocs :-) [...] Yes, I'm willing to participate.
                Let me hear when you got something started."

To be honest, I hate the 'assigned' word here :) I think the best thing I
can do now, is to adapt my sources, add comments etc. so that I can start up
the Encyclopedia as soon as possible with useful/learnful stuff.

I'll scan through my sources later, and compile some kind of... well
compilation with usefull stuff.

Things that come to mind:
Creating GUI's. WB/Shell arguments parsing. Inline asm. OOP, classes etc.
Using fonts. Using BOOPSI. Utility.library

My style of writing an E doc would be using many, clearly
documented/commented examples. I've a respect for those who can write
manuals like the AutoDocs, as they're written very clearly and efficient.


